    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">${(revenueHistory[4] ? revenueHistory[4].value / 1000 : revenue2025 / 1000).toFixed(1)}B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">FY2025 Revenue</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">${(fcf2025 / 1000).toFixed(2)}B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Free Cash Flow</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">${(epsHistory[4] ? epsHistory[4].value : 13.22).toFixed(2)}</div>
      <div class="stat-label">EPS (Diluted)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">${(marginHistory[4] ? marginHistory[4].operating : 6.3).toFixed(1)}%</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Operating Margin</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">${(netCash / 1000).toFixed(1)}B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Net Cash</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ METHODOLOGY ═══ -->
  <h2>Methodology: Two-Stage DCF</h2>
  <p>We use a <strong>two-stage discounted cash flow (DCF)</strong> model — the gold standard of intrinsic valuation. No multiples, no comparables, no vibes. Just future cash flows discounted to today.</p>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">1</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Start with actual Free Cash Flow</h4>
      <p>Marathon Petroleum generated <strong>$${(fcf2025 / 1000).toFixed(2)} billion</strong> in free cash flow in FY2025. This is real cash the business produces after paying for everything, from day-to-day operations to refining capacity upkeep.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">2</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Project FCF growth for 5 years (Phase 1)</h4>
      <p>We project FCF to grow at <strong>2% per year</strong> for 5 years. This is a very conservative assumption recognizing that the massive FCF generated in 2022 ($30.2B) was an anomaly due to extreme market conditions. The refining environment has normalized, and a 2% growth accurately reflects mature industry growth amidst energy transitions.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">3</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Calculate terminal value (Phase 2)</h4>
      <p>After Year 5, we assume FCF grows at <strong>1.5% forever</strong>. This is below the long-term historical inflation rate, accounting for the long-term headwinds in fossil fuel consumption and the gradual transition to renewable energy sources over several decades.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">4</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Discount everything to present value</h4>
      <p>All future cash flows are discounted at <strong>9%</strong> — our required rate of return. This aligns with MPC's lower beta (0.71) and relatively strong midstream and refining moat, offering a fair premium above the 10Y Treasury (4.18%).</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">5</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Subtract net debt, divide by shares</h4>
      <p>Enterprise Value + Net Cash (-$30.7B) = Equity Value. Divide by shares outstanding (306M) for the per-share intrinsic value.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ THE THREE ASSUMPTIONS ═══ -->
  <h2>The Three Assumptions That Drive Everything</h2>
  <p>A DCF is only as good as its inputs. We're making exactly <strong>three</strong> judgment calls — everything else is math. Here's what we chose and why.</p>

  <div class="assumption-grid">
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">FCF Growth Rate (Years 1-5)</div>
      <div class="value">2%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Refining margins have normalized heavily since the 2022 highs. FCF dropped from over $30B to below $5B. We do not expect another super-cycle in the next 5 years, so we assign a modest 2% growth from this new base, driven primarily by operational efficiencies and logistics segments.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Discount Rate (WACC)</div>
      <div class="value">9%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        10Y Treasury: 4.18%. Equity risk premium: ~5.5%. Beta: 0.71. A strict CAPM calculation gives ~8.1%. We conservatively round up to 9% to account for cyclical and regulatory risks in the refining sector, effectively demanding a higher return for owning a cyclical asset.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Terminal Growth Rate</div>
      <div class="value">1.5%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Long-term nominal GDP growth is ~3%. However, terminal growth for a traditional refining business must account for peak oil demand and EV adoption over the very long term. 1.5% assumes the business persists and manages a gentle decline in volumes offset by pricing or renewable fuel ventures.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

