  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. Here's what a DCF inherently misses — and how it might bias our estimate.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Refining Supercycle:</strong> If geopolitical tensions or unexpected demand shocks occur, refining margins (crack spreads) could skyrocket again, dramatically boosting FCF in the short term.</li>
    <li><strong>Aggressive Buybacks:</strong> MPC has historically retired a massive percentage of its shares. If they continue deploying FCF into aggressive share repurchases, per-share value will compound faster than the business grows.</li>
    <li><strong>MPLX Ownership:</strong> Marathon owns a majority stake in MPLX (a midstream master limited partnership), providing a stable, growing stream of cash distributions that can offset refining volatility.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>EV Adoption Acceleration:</strong> A faster-than-expected global shift to electric vehicles could permanently impair domestic gasoline and diesel demand, pushing terminal growth negative.</li>
    <li><strong>Regulatory Burdens:</strong> Increasing environmental regulations, carbon taxes, or changes to the Renewable Fuel Standard (RFS) could significantly raise operating costs.</li>
    <li><strong>Economic Recession:</strong> Refining is highly cyclical. An economic downturn would hit fuel demand and margins simultaneously, depressing near-term cash flows.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why is the estimated intrinsic value so far below the current price?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Marathon's free cash flow has plummeted from over $30B in 2022 to just $4.77B in 2025. Meanwhile, the stock price has remained resilient, partly due to massive share buybacks and yield. Our DCF model strictly prices the cash the business is generating today and in the future; if the market is pricing in a return to higher refining margins or attributing a premium to the MPLX stake, our conservative cash flow projections will result in a lower fair value estimate.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>How does the MPLX stake factor into this valuation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">The cash distributions MPC receives from its stake in MPLX are fully captured in the consolidated Free Cash Flow we used as the baseline for this model. We evaluate the enterprise as a whole based on the cash it ultimately generates.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why use a 2% growth rate when historical growth has been so volatile?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Refining is inherently cyclical. Using a very high growth rate after a cyclical peak is dangerous, but penalizing the company with negative growth off a depressed base might be too pessimistic. We chose 2% as a middle ground representing normalized operational improvements over a typical cycle.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a sell recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value based on specific assumptions. The market often values capital return programs (buybacks and dividends) heavily in this sector. Whether to buy or sell depends on your personal risk tolerance and conviction in the underlying assumptions.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

